      {
        "title": "All Six Heading Levels in a Realistic Document",
        "description": "This example shows all six heading levels in a real technical documentation article. Every level is contextually justified and shows the parent-child outline relationship. It also shows how CSS can independently control visual size without changing the semantic rank of any heading.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>API Security Guide | DevDocs</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: Georgia, serif; max-width: 720px;\n           margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem; line-height: 1.7; }\n\n    /* CSS controls visual size. HTML controls semantic rank. These are independent. */\n    h1 { font-size: 2rem;    color: #0f172a; margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }\n    h2 { font-size: 1.5rem;  color: #1e293b; margin-top: 2rem;\n         border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0; padding-bottom: 0.25rem; }\n    h3 { font-size: 1.2rem;  color: #334155; margin-top: 1.5rem; }\n    h4 { font-size: 1rem;    color: #475569; margin-top: 1.25rem; }\n    h5 { font-size: 0.9rem;  color: #64748b; font-style: italic; }\n    h6 { font-size: 0.85rem; color: #94a3b8; text-transform: uppercase;\n         letter-spacing: 0.05em; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <!-- h1: page title, one per page, matches the <title> element closely -->\n  <h1>API Security Guide</h1>\n  <p>A complete reference for securing REST APIs in production environments.</p>\n\n  <!-- h2: major top-level sections of the page -->\n  <h2>Authentication Methods</h2>\n  <p>Choosing the right authentication method is the first security decision for any API.</p>\n\n    <!-- h3: subsection inside Authentication Methods -->\n    <h3>API Keys</h3>\n    <p>Simple shared secrets passed as a header or query parameter.</p>\n\n      <!-- h4: a detail topic inside API Keys -->\n      <h4>When to Use API Keys</h4>\n      <p>Appropriate for server-to-server communication where the client is trusted.</p>\n\n      <h4>Key Rotation Best Practices</h4>\n      <p>Rotate keys every 90 days and immediately upon any suspected compromise.</p>\n\n    <h3>OAuth 2.0</h3>\n    <p>Delegates authentication to a trusted identity provider.</p>\n\n      <h4>Authorization Code Flow</h4>\n      <p>For web apps where the client secret can be stored securely on the server.</p>\n\n        <!-- h5: a specification note within Authorization Code Flow -->\n        <h5>PKCE Extension</h5>\n        <p>Adds a cryptographic verifier to prevent authorization code interception.</p>\n\n          <!-- h6: a reference detail inside PKCE, very rarely needed outside technical docs -->\n          <h6>RFC Reference</h6>\n          <p>Defined in RFC 7636. Required for all public clients since the OAuth 2.1 draft.</p>\n\n      <h4>Client Credentials Flow</h4>\n      <p>For machine-to-machine communication with no user involved.</p>\n\n  <!-- h2 again: next major section, valid return to level 2 -->\n  <h2>Rate Limiting</h2>\n  <p>Protects APIs from abuse and ensures fair resource allocation.</p>\n\n    <h3>Token Bucket Algorithm</h3>\n    <p>Tokens replenish at a fixed rate. Each request consumes one token.</p>\n\n    <h3>Sliding Window Algorithm</h3>\n    <p>Tracks request counts over a rolling time window for smoother enforcement.</p>\n\n  <h2>Error Response Standards</h2>\n  <p>Consistent error responses are as important as consistent success responses.</p>\n\n    <h3>HTTP Status Code Selection</h3>\n    <p>Return 401 for unauthenticated, 403 for unauthorised, 429 for rate limited.</p>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
