        "title": "Headings, SEO Keywords, and the sr-only Pattern",
        "description": "This example shows how heading hierarchy directly affects SEO keyword weighting and introduces the sr-only visually-hidden heading pattern. The sr-only technique labels regions like sidebars and footers for screen reader navigation without adding visible headings that would disrupt the design.",
        "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>React State Management Guide | DevDocs India</title>\n  <style>\n    body { font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 720px; margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem; }\n\n    /*\n      sr-only: removes element from visual layout but keeps it\n      in the accessibility tree and heading navigation list.\n      Screen reader users hear the heading. Sighted users do not see it.\n    */\n    .sr-only {\n      position: absolute;\n      width: 1px; height: 1px;\n      padding: 0; margin: -1px;\n      overflow: hidden;\n      clip: rect(0,0,0,0);\n      white-space: nowrap;\n      border: 0;\n    }\n\n    nav.crumb { font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-bottom: 1rem; }\n    nav.crumb a { color: #2563eb; text-decoration: none; }\n    .tag { background:#dbeafe; color:#1d4ed8; padding:0.15rem 0.5rem;\n           border-radius:999px; font-size:0.75rem; margin-right:0.3rem; }\n    aside { background:#f8fafc; border-radius:8px; padding:1rem; margin:1.5rem 0; }\n    .links { list-style:none; padding:0; margin:0; }\n    .links li { padding:0.3rem 0; border-bottom:1px solid #e5e7eb; }\n    .links li:last-child { border-bottom:none; }\n    footer { margin-top: 2rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid #e5e7eb; }\n    footer nav { display:flex; gap:1rem; }\n    footer a { color:#6b7280; font-size:0.85rem; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <nav class=\"crumb\" aria-label=\"Breadcrumb\">\n    <a href=\"/\">Home</a> /\n    <a href=\"/react\">React</a> /\n    <span>State Management</span>\n  </nav>\n\n  <!--\n    h1 carries the primary keyword for this page.\n    Search engines give h1 the highest on-page keyword weight.\n    It should match or closely mirror the <title> element.\n  -->\n  <h1>React State Management: useState, useReducer, and Context</h1>\n  <p><span class=\"tag\">React 18</span><span class=\"tag\">Intermediate</span></p>\n\n  <!--\n    h2 elements carry secondary keywords.\n    Each h2 signals a major subtopic that search engines index independently.\n  -->\n  <h2>When to Use useState</h2>\n  <p>Correct for local, independent, component-level state that does not\n  need to be shared with other components.</p>\n\n  <h2>When to Use useReducer</h2>\n  <p>Handles complex state with multiple sub-values or where the next state\n  depends on the previous in non-trivial ways.</p>\n\n    <h3>Reducer Pattern vs useState Pattern</h3>\n    <p>useReducer centralises all state transitions in one pure function,\n    making complex state changes auditable and testable.</p>\n\n  <h2>Context API for Shared State</h2>\n  <p>React Context solves prop drilling but is not a general-purpose\n  replacement for dedicated state libraries in large applications.</p>\n\n\n  <!--\n    sr-only heading on an aside:\n    The sidebar is visually obvious to sighted users.\n    Screen reader users navigating by headings would pass it with no label.\n    The sr-only h2 adds it to the heading outline without showing a visible heading.\n  -->\n  <aside>\n    <h2 class=\"sr-only\">Related Articles</h2>\n    <ul class=\"links\">\n      <li><a href=\"/react/hooks\">React Hooks Complete Guide</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"/react/context\">React Context Deep Dive</a></li>\n      <li><a href=\"/react/redux\">Redux vs Context: When to Use Each</a></li>\n    </ul>\n  </aside>\n\n\n  <!--\n    Footer uses sr-only h2 so screen reader users can jump\n    to the footer section via heading navigation.\n  -->\n  <footer>\n    <h2 class=\"sr-only\">Footer Navigation</h2>\n    <nav aria-label=\"Footer\">\n      <a href=\"/privacy\">Privacy</a>\n      <a href=\"/terms\">Terms</a>\n      <a href=\"/contact\">Contact</a>\n    </nav>\n  </footer>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
