          "title": "Broken vs Correct Heading Hierarchy with Live Outline Inspector",
          "description": "This example places a broken and a corrected heading structure side by side with identical content. All headings are forced to the same visual size with CSS to demonstrate that hierarchy is structural, not visual. A JavaScript outline builder reads both columns and annotates each heading, flagging skipped levels and duplicate h1 elements.",
          "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n  <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n  <title>Heading Hierarchy: Broken vs Correct</title>\n  <style>\n    body  { font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 960px; margin: 2rem auto; padding: 0 1rem; }\n    .cols { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }\n    .box  { border: 1px solid #e5e7eb; border-radius: 8px; padding: 1.25rem; }\n    .bad  { border-color: #dc2626; background: #fef2f2; }\n    .good { border-color: #16a34a; background: #f0fdf4; }\n    .label { font-size: 0.7rem; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase;\n             letter-spacing: 0.06em; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }\n    .bad  .label { color: #dc2626; }\n    .good .label { color: #16a34a; }\n\n    /*\n      All headings inside demo boxes are forced to the same visual size.\n      This proves that heading level is a structural decision, not a visual one.\n      Only CSS changes can make them look different, not the element choice.\n    */\n    .box h1,.box h2,.box h3,.box h4,.box h5 {\n      font-size: 0.95rem;\n      font-weight: 600;\n      margin: 0.5rem 0 0.15rem;\n      color: #1e293b;\n    }\n    .box p { margin: 0 0 0.4rem; font-size: 0.85rem; color: #475569; }\n\n    .outline { background: #0f172a; color: #e2e8f0; border-radius: 6px;\n               padding: 0.75rem 1rem; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.78rem;\n               white-space: pre; margin-top: 0.5rem; }\n    .outline .warn { color: #fca5a5; }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <h1>Heading Hierarchy: Broken vs Correct</h1>\n  <p>Both columns contain identical content. All headings inside are forced to\n  the same visual size with CSS to show hierarchy is structural, not visual.</p>\n\n  <div class=\"cols\">\n\n    <!-- BROKEN: three issues annotated inline -->\n    <div class=\"box bad\" id=\"box-bad\">\n      <p class=\"label\">Broken Hierarchy</p>\n\n      <h1>Online Courses Platform</h1>   <!-- issue: second h1 on the page -->\n\n      <!-- issue: jumps h1 to h3, h2 is missing -->\n      <h3>Web Development</h3>\n\n      <!-- issue: jumps h3 to h5, h4 is missing -->\n      <h5>HTML and CSS</h5>\n      <p>Beginner, 12 hours.</p>\n\n      <h5>JavaScript</h5>\n      <p>Intermediate, 20 hours.</p>\n\n      <h3>Design Courses</h3>\n\n      <h5>Figma Basics</h5>\n      <p>UI design, 8 hours.</p>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- CORRECT: clean incremental hierarchy -->\n    <div class=\"box good\" id=\"box-good\">\n      <p class=\"label\">Correct Hierarchy</p>\n\n      <!-- h2: no second h1, this section sits below the page h1 above -->\n      <h2>Online Courses Platform</h2>\n\n      <!-- h3: direct child of h2, no skip -->\n      <h3>Web Development</h3>\n\n      <!-- h4: direct child of h3, no skip -->\n      <h4>HTML and CSS</h4>\n      <p>Beginner, 12 hours.</p>\n\n      <h4>JavaScript</h4>\n      <p>Intermediate, 20 hours.</p>\n\n      <!-- h3 again: valid return to major section level -->\n      <h3>Design Courses</h3>\n\n      <h4>Figma Basics</h4>\n      <p>UI design, 8 hours.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n\n  <h2>Live Outline Inspector</h2>\n  <div class=\"cols\">\n    <div>\n      <strong style=\"font-size:0.85rem;\">Broken outline:</strong>\n      <div class=\"outline\" id=\"out-bad\"></div>\n    </div>\n    <div>\n      <strong style=\"font-size:0.85rem;\">Correct outline:</strong>\n      <div class=\"outline\" id=\"out-good\"></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <script>\n    function buildOutline(boxId) {\n      const box = document.getElementById(boxId);\n      const hs  = box.querySelectorAll('h1,h2,h3,h4,h5,h6');\n      let prev = 0;\n      let firstH1Found = false;\n      const pageH1Level = 1; // the page already has an h1\n\n      return [...hs].map(h => {\n        const lvl    = parseInt(h.tagName[1]);\n        const indent = '  '.repeat(Math.max(0, lvl - 1));\n        const text   = h.textContent.trim();\n        let note = '';\n\n        if (lvl === 1) {\n          note = firstH1Found ? ' <- SECOND h1 on page' : ' <- h1 (page-level)';\n          firstH1Found = true;\n        } else if (prev > 0 && lvl > prev + 1) {\n          note = ` <- SKIP: h${prev} -> h${lvl} (missing h${prev + 1})`;\n        }\n\n        prev = lvl;\n        return `${indent}h${lvl}: ${text}${note}`;\n      }).join('\\n');\n    }\n\n    document.getElementById('out-bad').textContent  = buildOutline('box-bad');\n    document.getElementById('out-good').textContent = buildOutline('box-good');\n  </script>\n\n</body>\n</html>",
          "output": "Page renders a two-column layout, both columns visually identical since all headings share the same CSS size. The broken outline panel shows: h1 flagged as SECOND h1 on page, then h3 with a SKIP warning showing h1 to h3 missing h2, then h5 with a SKIP warning showing h3 to h5 missing h4. The correct outline panel shows a clean tree: h2, h3, h4, h4, h3, h4 with no warnings.",
